   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Programming exercise week 4\n",
    "## Programming exercise 4.3\n",
    "In this task the K-means algorithm shall be implemented and applied."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### (a)\n",
    "Implement the K-means algorithm by yourself, see Fig. 7.3 in the book."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def k_means(X, k, n_iters, verbose=5, seed=None):\n",
    "    np.random.seed(seed) # set random seed for reproducibility\n",
    "    N = X.shape[0] # the number of data points\n",
    "    dim = X.shape[1] # the dimensionality of the data points (number of features)\n",
    "    ms = X[np.random.choice(N, size=k)] # the cluster centers, randomly picked among the points\n",
    "    \n",
    "    for i in range(n_iters):\n",
    "        ### EXPECTATION STEP\n",
    "        # we start by finding the distances between all pairs of points and cluster centers\n",
    "        dists_to_centers = [np.linalg.norm(X-m, axis=1) ** 2 for m in ms]\n",
    "        # we find the index for the closest center to each point\n",
    "        rs = np.argmin(dists_to_centers, axis=0)\n",
    "        \n",
    "        ### MAXIMIZATION STEP\n",
    "        # we calculate each cluster center as the mean of the points assigned to the cluster\n",
    "        for j in range(k):\n",
    "            ms[j] = X[np.flatnonzero(rs==j)].mean(axis=0)\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # we calculate the error every now and then\n",
    "        if i % verbose == 0:\n",
    "            # we could check how much the error changes and stop when it changes very little (converged)\n",
    "            error = np.min([np.linalg.norm(X-m, axis=1) ** 2 for m in ms], axis=0).sum()\n",
    "            print(\"iteration: {}   error: {:.2f}\".format(i,error))\n",
    "        \n",
    "    # we return rs (the cluster for each point) and ks (the center of each cluster)\n",
    "    return rs, ms"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### (b)\n",
    "The file `iris.txt` contains the Iris data set. It consists of a total of 150 samples, with 50 for each of the three classes, while each sample is composed of 4 values, hence the data matrix $\\mathbf{X} \\in \\mathbb{R}^{150\\times4}$. Choose $K=3$ to estimate the three classes by your implementation of the K-means clustering, i.e. for each data point $\\mathbf{x}_i \\in \\mathbb{R}^4$ assign one of three classes.\n",
    "\n",
    "*Hint*: Consider that the absolute values of the true and estimated labels can differ. In the following example the three classes are 100% correctly estimated:\\\n",
    "provided true labels: 1, 1, 2, 3, 3\\\n",
    "estimated labels:     0, 0, 3, 2, 2\n",
    "\n",
    "We start by downloading and loading in the data set from sklearn:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.datasets import load_iris\n",
    "iris = load_iris()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Separate the input variables $\\mathbf{x}_i$ from the target variables $t_i$ in two different arrays."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "((150, 4), (150,))"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 4,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "X = iris.data # data; each row is an observation, each column is a feature\n",
    "t = iris.target\n",
    "X.shape, t.shape"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The exercise tells us to run the K-means algorithm for all four features with $K=3$, i.e. we assume three clusters, and we'll run 20 iterations."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "K = 3\n",
    "iterations = 20"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now we run the K-means algorithm using all four features (columns)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "iteration: 0   error: 85.26\n",
      "iteration: 5   error: 79.87\n",
      "iteration: 10   error: 78.86\n",
      "iteration: 15   error: 78.86\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "rs, ms = k_means(X, K, iterations, seed=456)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "So, how did we do compared to the true labels? That is, did our clusters group together the data points that belong to the same classes? We use the following function to transform our random cluster labels to match with the class labels, i.e. if we predict (0,0,2,2,1,1) but the true labels are (1,1,2,2,0,0), we want to return (1,1,2,2,0,0), since we got them all rightly grouped!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from scipy.stats import mode\n",
    "\n",
    "def transform_clusters_to_classes(true, pred, n_clusters):\n",
    "    labels = np.zeros(rs.shape)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    for k in range(n_clusters):\n",
    "        cluster_idxs = (pred==k)\n",
    "        labels[cluster_idxs] = mode(true[cluster_idxs])[0]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    return labels"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "So, how many did we get right and wrong?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "We got 133 right and 17 wrong.\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "preds = transform_clusters_to_classes(t, rs, K)\n",
    "right = (t==preds).sum()\n",
    "wrong = (t!=preds).sum()\n",
    "print(\"We got {} right and {} wrong.\".format(right, wrong))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "That is, we made 17 mistakes out of 150, which is about 89% accuracy."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

    "Remember that the initialization is based on random samples and hence the outcome will differ if you repeat the experiments. For a better comparison choose the same $K$ random starting samples each version.\n",

    "combs = [(0,1), (0,2), (0,3), (1,2), (1,3), (2,3)]\n",

   ]

   "source": [
